Table 3
 shows the antibacterial properties of composite films with different CDs concentrations against E. coli and S. aureus. The PVA film exhibits almost no antibacterial effect. With the addition of CDs, the low - concentration (0.2 %) CDs/PVA composite film shows a certain antibacterial effect on the two bacteria, and the number of colonies is significantly reduced. In the composite film with a high concentration of CDs (0.6 %), the antibacterial performance is further enhanced, and the antibacterial rates against E. coli and S. aureus reach 85 % and 87 % respectively (Fig. 9
). This remarkable antibacterial effect may be related to the high specific surface area of CDs. CDs cause mechanical damage through physical contact with the bacterial cell wall, and at the same time, their chemical groups can disrupt the biological structure of bacteria [46]. Among them, the antibacterial effect of the composite film on S. aureus is slightly stronger than that on E. coli. This may be because the thicker cell wall of Gram - positive bacteria is more vulnerable to the attack of the chemical groups on the surface of CDs, while the double - membrane structure of Gram - negative bacteria provides some protection [47].
